   {:e #blake3 "939915f71a1a111d004c6769ca3367e0b9a8cf0a44ee4b5427ba4adc1d0d58b4" :a :task/description :v "CONTEXT: 4 independent audit agents produced 226 observations. Many describe the same finding (e.g. F(S) monotonicity falsified appears in all 4 reports). The store treats each as independent — no mechanism detects that 4 sources agree on the same defect. Corroboration is the strongest epistemic signal: independent agreement is more certain than any single high-confidence observation. RATIONALE: The concept engine (concept.rs) already performs agglomerative clustering via embeddings. After clustering, compute corroboration_score = distinct_agent_count / total_agents_in_session. P(defect | 4 independent reports) >> P(defect | 1 report). This is Bayesian updating across independent sources. APPROACH: (1) After concept clustering, for each cluster collect the set of distinct :tx/agent values from the observation transactions. (2) Add corroboration_score = |distinct_agents| / |total_session_agents| to ConceptSummary. (3) Add confidence_range (min, max, mean) across cluster members. (4) Store as :concept/corroboration (Double, One) and :concept/agent-count (Long, One) datoms. (5) Surface in braid status concept section: 'f-s-monotonicity (4/4 agents, confidence 0.85-0.95)'. ACCEPTANCE: (A) After running on 226 audit observations, top cluster contains F(S) monotonicity finding with corroboration >= 3/4. (B) ConceptSummary has corroboration_score field. (C) braid status shows agent count per concept. CONSIDERATIONS: The HashEmbedder concept-collapse problem (AUDIT-EXT CONCEPT-COLLAPSE) may merge distinct findings into one mega-cluster. If so, this task surfaces the problem clearly (one cluster with corroboration 4/4 and 200 observations = obviously collapsed). The corroboration signal is still useful even with imperfect clustering — it just operates at a coarser granularity. DEPENDS-ON: t-7716255c (C9 EPIC). FILE: crates/braid-kernel/src/concept.rs." :op :assert}
